data.title: Straight Outta Compton has it all wrong says NWA manager Jerry Heller
data.meta_description: Jerry Heller, the white, Jewish manager of NWA as they rose to worldwide fame, has offered a racially different version of their story from the movie, saying Dr. Dre was the villain, not Eazy-E.
data.text:
He is the former manager of 1980s rappers NWA who was cast as the villain in the hit biopic 'Straight Outta Compton'.

But Jerry Heller claims that he was not to blame for the backstabbing which ended the group he called 'The Black Beatles'.

In his memoir he pointed the finger at the group's producer Dr Dre and accused him of 'betraying' the group's founder and owner Eazy-E.

Heller claims that Dre set up E to get blackmailed into freeing him from his contract in a deceit that puts to shame the respectable producer he is today who sold his Beats headphones to Apple for $700 million.

Scroll down for video

Heller wrote that he bitterly regretted how he 'failed' NWA because he did not think that Dre would stoop so low.

He wrote: 'I couldn't imagine anyone coming in between the two most crucial members of the group - Eazy E and Dr Dre.'

'I couldn't grasp the idea that two people could be that tight, could have that much history and reach the pinnacle of fame and success together and then have one turned around and betray the other.

'I didn't have that level of understanding of the human animal. I guess that even after three decades I had spent in the rough-and-tumble music business, in a corner of my soul I was naive'.

The claims are the latest example of how Straight Outta Compton has been accused of whitewashing the band's checkered past.

The movie is about the five men; Dre, E, Ice Cube, MC Ren and DJ Yella, who brought gangster rap to the mainstream with NWA - which stands for N****s With Attitude - before splitting after four years together.

The movie, which has been no.1 in the box office for two weeks, broadly takes the side of Dre and Cube; E and Heller are portrayed a the bad guys as they take all the group's money for themselves at the expense of everyone else.

But in 'Ruthless: A Memoir', which Heller wrote in 2006, he tells a different story as his time as manager of NWA and Ruthless Records, their label.

He says that he and E hit it off right away even though they were an unlikely match and that they always looked out for each other.

Heller was a middle-aged white Jewish man who served in the Army and had represented Black Sabbath and Elton John.

E was a drug dealer from Compton, a crack-ridden neighborhood in Los Angeles overrun by gangs.

Heller claims that he put the first $250,000 into Ruthless followed by 'a million over the first few years of the label's existence'.

E's money from drug dealing also went into the kitty.

Ruthless had three checking accounts and Heller and E were signatories on both, meaning they both had to sign off on everything.

As Heller writes, the label was entirely owned by E; he got 80 per cent of the profits and Heller got 20 per cent of everything else.

But he is not as clear on the rest of the finances as he could be.

Heller says that everyone in the band was given a check for $75,000 when they were on their first world tour, a scene that features in the film.

But he also says that the group were raking in tens of millions of dollars a month.

The apparent disparity is never explained.

Heller describes himself as E's 'mentor and confidante' and his 'stalwart defender'.

He said that E 'freed Dre to be who he really wanted to be' and gave him a 'chance to create from the gritty world they both move in'.

Heller hated Cube from the start and writes that 'even in those early days (he) was always difficult'.

He says that Cube 'had a chip on his shoulder' and had an 'adolescent attitude' but admits: 'S***y human beings sometimes make great art'.

Cube was the first to leave the group but it was Dre's departure that brought about the end in 1991.

Heller claims that Dre was influenced by the Ruthless signing D.O.C., who had fallen under the influence of Suge Knight, Bobby Brown's former bodyguard who was muscling his way into the music management business.

His way in was as a bodyguard for Ruthless, but he soon set eyes on Heller's job.

Describing Knight, Heller writes: 'It was like we were all partying around the bonfire and somewhere out there in the darkness a bear was prowling, hungry but too afraid of the flames to actually come and attack.'

Knight and his henchmen would physically intimidate Heller around the Ruthless office until he hired his own bodyguards. Then the intimidation continued in the form of late night phone calls or being tailed when he got home.

Among the many lies told by Dre was that he was broke, Heller claims.

Before the group split he claims to have found a drawer full of checks from rival acts and producers that Dre had been making music for without Heller's knowledge.

One was for $12,000. When Heller asked Dre about it, he supposedly replied: 'I guess stuff kinda gets away from me.'

The end came came on April 23 1991. Heller writes that Dre and E had been squabbling and that Dre called him to try to make peace.

As E described it, Dre told him: 'Hey yo, you know we got to work this s*** out...This is important. You want to get with me here?'

Dre told E to meet him at the Galaxy Studios of Sounds of Los Angeles Records and Heller says that E thought it was 'just two homies working out their differences'.

E had already told Dre he could produce anybody he wanted, so long as he stayed at Ruthless, anything to keep the group together.

Heller writes: 'When (E) enters the building and heads up to the third floor of the wood and glass Galaxy Studios, the place feels wrong, deserted.

'No Dre. Instantly Eazy realizes he has been set up'.

Knight tells him he has to sign the papers releasing to him Dre, the D.O.C. and Michel'le, Dre's girlfriend and a best-selling R&B singer.

Knight supposedly tells him: 'We got Jerry Heller tied up in the back of (a) van, gun to his head, blow his goddam f****** brains out. We can get your (mom) too. You want us to?'

The movie omits all of this but shows E getting beaten up by Knight and his henchmen who are carrying baseball bats.

Either way the result is the same - E signs the papers.

Heller writes that during a final, painful sit down talk later on E asked Dre: 'Do you know about this?'

Dre supposedly replied: 'No' but as Heller points out, it wasn't clear if he meant: 'No I didn't set you up' or: 'No, I won't answer you'.

Heller says that he wrote his memoir to set the record straight.

Because of what he says are lies spread by Dre and Cube and disrespectful raps - Cube's 'No Vaseline' includes the line: 'Ain't nobody humping me' - his name is muck in the entertainment industry.

In the song Cube also rapped: 'It's a case of divide-and-conquer, cuz you let a Jew break up my crew. House n**** gotta run and hide, yellin' Compton, but you moved to Riverside.'

Heller writes that he is seen as 'The Great Satan of rap music' but the reality is different.

Heller writes: 'Eazy-E saw his best friend, the brilliant Andre Young, Dr Dre, betray him. They had come up together on the violent streets of Compton.

'O'Shea Jackson, aka Ice Cube...turned on Eazy (too) with casual viciousness, ridiculing him, dissing him repeatedly, battering him in rap after rap'.

Among the other things that Straight Outta Compton has been accused of is whitewashing the violence towards women on the behalf of the group's members.

Journalist Dee Barnes has claimed that Dre threw her down a flight of stairs and and beat her in 1991 at a Hollywood record party because he did not like her showing a clip of Cube on her Fox TV show Pump it Up!

Dre pleaded no contest to assault and served two years probation. Barnes sued and settled out of court for a sum she later said was less than $1 million.

In his book Heller recalls the incident as 'one of the most disgraceful episodes in the Ruthless saga'.

He says that Dre went 'medieval on her a**, slamming her face into a stairwell wall' then when she fled into a bathroom Dre 'followed her in and pummeled her some more'.

Nobody for Dre was available for comment.

He has previously apologized for his violence towards women and in a letter to the New York Times said sorry to 'the women I've hurt'.

Straight Outta Compton director F. Gary Gray has said that when he was making the fiilm that Dre was on the set every day while Cube was heavily involved in the development and post-production.

Heller appears to have have little input, if any.

Asked by The Independent why he took Dre and Cub's side, Gray said: 'I just took first-hand accounts from people who dealt with all the characters.

'Jerry or Suge or whoever, I read books and watched videos, I feel good about the information that I received and what is put in the movie.'

Reached on the phone Heller declined to comment.
